Preheat your #oven to 200°C. Bring a large #saucepan of water up to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp} for the potatoes. Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm chunks (peel them first if you prefer a smoother mash). Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed, no need to peel) and grate on the coarse side of your #grater.

Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until you can easily slip a knife through them, ~{15-20%minutes}. Drain in a #colander, then return to the pan off the heat. Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan on high heat (no oil). When hot, add the @lamb mince{200} and cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Break it up with a #wooden spoon as it cooks. Drain off any excess fat.

Stir the carrot into the lamb mince, then add the @dried oregano{1}. Pour in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(400g can), @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @water{50%ml} and @sugar{2%tsp}. Bring to the boil, stirring to dissolve the stock pot. Reduce the heat to medium and simmer until thick and tomatoey, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150}. Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}.

Once drained and back in the pan, add a knob of @butter{1%knob} and a splash of @?milk{} (if you have any) to the potatoes. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Mash the potato with a #potato masher then fold through the spring onion. Pour the lamb mixture into an #ovenproof dish{}. Spread the spring onion mash out on top, using the back of a #spoon to ensure it covers the lamb evenly. Bake until piping hot and golden on top, ~{12-15%minutes}.

While the pie bakes, rinse out the lamb pan and return to medium heat. Add the green beans and a splash of @water{}. Pop a #lid (or some #foil) on the pan and leave to steam-fry until the beans are just tender, ~{6-8%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Serve the shepherd's pie with the beans alongside. Enjoy!